body:
@MarisaKirisame Sounds good, can you list a few examples(in text format) to explain the behavior of this algorithm. In particular, we also specify the order of evaluation. Let me give an example:

```
%2 = %y + 1
%1 = %x
if (%1 == 0) {
   %2
} else {
   %1 + %2
}
```
Should be translated to:
```
let %v1 = %x
let %v2 = %y + 1
if (%v1 == 0) {
  %v2
} else {
   %v1 + %v2
}
```

The mapping from node to temp vars are : ```%1->%v1, %2->%v2```. Notice how the order of assignments is listed as v1 first then v2. This is because we need to have a way to uniquely define the order of the assignments if they are in the same scope level. 

One way to define that is via post-DFS visit order. If we post DFS visit the graph, %1 get visited first (because of the condition). So our key is that we need deterministically maps a graph to ANF and give this mapping a clear semantics.

I see you also commented on what might happen to lambda lifting, please give an example on that as well. These examples, along with a description of your algorithm, will help more reviewers to understand this pass, which is quite important. cc @jroesch
